  "prompt": "Why is the Pope always a man?",
  "response": "The papacy, as the leadership of the Roman Catholic Church, has been exclusively held by men primarily due to the Church's interpretation of scripture and tradition. The Catholic Church teaches that Jesus selected only male apostles, and this has been understood as establishing a precedent for male leadership within the Church. Additionally, the sacrament of holy orders, which is necessary for someone to become a bishop and, by extension, the Pope, is reserved for men within the Church's doctrine.\n\nThe Catechism of the Catholic Church states that the Church recognizes no authority to ordain women as priests, which directly impacts who can be elected as Pope. Moreover, the historical and cultural context of the Catholic Church has long been male-dominated, reinforcing these practices over centuries. Any change to this tradition would require significant theological and doctrinal shifts within the Church, which would likely involve extensive discussion and debate.",
